format/markdown.md
     1→# Markdown
     2→
     3→mdBook's [parser](https://github.com/raphlinus/pulldown-cmark) adheres to the [CommonMark](https://commonmark.org/) specification with some extensions described below.
     4→You can take a quick [tutorial](https://commonmark.org/help/tutorial/),
     5→or [try out](https://spec.commonmark.org/dingus/) CommonMark in real time. A complete Markdown overview is out of scope for 
     6→this documentation, but below is a high level overview of some of the basics. For a more in-depth experience, check out the
     7→[Markdown Guide](https://www.markdownguide.org).
     8→
     9→## Text and paragraphs
    10→
    11→Text is rendered relatively predictably: 
    12→
    13→```markdown
    14→Here is a line of text.
    15→
    16→This is a new line.
    17→```
    18→
    19→Will look like you might expect:
    20→
    21→Here is a line of text.
    22→
    23→This is a new line.
    24→
    25→## Headings
    26→
    27→Headings use the `#` marker and should be on a line by themselves. More `#` mean smaller headings:
    28→
    29→```markdown
    30→### A heading 
    31→
    32→Some text.
    33→
    34→#### A smaller heading 
    35→
    36→More text.
    37→```
    38→
    39→### A heading 
    40→
    41→Some text.
    42→
    43→#### A smaller heading 
    44→
    45→More text.
    46→
    47→## Lists
    48→
    49→Lists can be unordered or ordered. Ordered lists will order automatically:
    50→
    51→```markdown
    52→* milk
    53→* eggs
    54→* butter
    55→
    56→1. carrots
    57→1. celery
    58→1. radishes
    59→```
    60→
    61→* milk
    62→* eggs
    63→* butter
    64→
    65→1. carrots
    66→1. celery
    67→1. radishes
    68→
    69→## Links
    70→
    71→Linking to a URL or local file is easy:
    72→
    73→```markdown
    74→Use [mdBook](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook). 
    75→
    76→Read about [mdBook](mdbook.md).
    77→
    78→And now [an mdBook link] that is not inline, unlike the above.
    79→
    80→A bare url: <https://www.rust-lang.org>.
    81→
    82→[an mdBook link]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook
    83→```
    84→
    85→Use [mdBook](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook). 
    86→
    87→Read about [mdBook](mdbook.md).
    88→
    89→And now [an mdBook link] that is not inline, unlike the above.
    90→
    91→A bare url: <https://www.rust-lang.org>.
    92→
    93→[an mdBook link]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook
    94→----
    95→
    96→Relative links that end with `.md` will be converted to the `.html` extension.
    97→It is recommended to use `.md` links when possible.
    98→This is useful when viewing the Markdown file outside of mdBook, for example on GitHub or GitLab which render Markdown automatically.
    99→
   100→Links to `README.md` will be converted to `index.html`.
   101→This is done since some services like GitHub render README files automatically, but web servers typically expect the root file to be called `index.html`.
   102→
   103→You can link to individual headings with `#` fragments.
   104→For example, `mdbook.md#text-and-paragraphs` would link to the [Text and Paragraphs](#text-and-paragraphs) section above.
   105→The ID is created by transforming the heading such as converting to lowercase and replacing spaces with dashes.
   106→You can click on any heading and look at the URL in your browser to see what the fragment looks like.
   107→
   108→## Images
   109→
   110→Including images is simply a matter of including a link to them, much like in the _Links_ section above. The following markdown
   111→includes the Rust logo SVG image found in the `images` directory at the same level as this file:
   112→
   113→```markdown
   114→![The Rust Logo](images/rust-logo-blk.svg)
   115→```
   116→
   117→Produces the following HTML when built with mdBook:
   118→
   119→```html
   120→<p><img src="images/rust-logo-blk.svg" alt="The Rust Logo" /></p>
   121→```
   122→
   123→Which, of course displays the image like so:
   124→
   125→![The Rust Logo](images/rust-logo-blk.svg)
   126→
   127→## Extensions
   128→
   129→mdBook has several extensions beyond the standard CommonMark specification.
   130→
   131→### Strikethrough
   132→
   133→Text may be rendered with a horizontal line through the center by wrapping the
   134→text with one or two tilde characters on each side:
   135→
   136→```text
   137→An example of ~~strikethrough text~~.
   138→```
   139→
   140→This example will render as:
   141→
   142→> An example of ~~strikethrough text~~.
   143→
   144→This follows the [GitHub Strikethrough extension][strikethrough].
   145→
   146→### Footnotes
   147→
   148→A footnote generates a small numbered link in the text which when clicked
   149→takes the reader to the footnote text at the bottom of the item. The footnote
   150→label is written similarly to a link reference with a caret at the front. The
   151→footnote text is written like a link reference definition, with the text
   152→following the label. Example:
   153→
   154→```text
   155→This is an example of a footnote[^note].
   156→
   157→[^note]: This text is the contents of the footnote, which will be rendered
   158→    towards the bottom.
   159→```
   160→
   161→This example will render as:
   162→
   163→> This is an example of a footnote[^note].
   164→>
   165→> [^note]: This text is the contents of the footnote, which will be rendered
   166→>     towards the bottom.
   167→
   168→The footnotes are automatically numbered based on the order the footnotes are
   169→written.
   170→
   171→### Tables
   172→
   173→Tables can be written using pipes and dashes to draw the rows and columns of
   174→the table. These will be translated to HTML table matching the shape. Example:
   175→
   176→```text
   177→| Header1 | Header2 |
   178→|---------|---------|
   179→| abc     | def     |
   180→```
   181→
   182→This example will render similarly to this:
   183→
   184→| Header1 | Header2 |
   185→|---------|---------|
   186→| abc     | def     |
   187→
   188→See the specification for the [GitHub Tables extension][tables] for more
   189→details on the exact syntax supported.
   190→
   191→### Task lists
   192→
   193→Task lists can be used as a checklist of items that have been completed.
   194→Example:
   195→
   196→```md
   197→- [x] Complete task
   198→- [ ] Incomplete task
   199→```
   200→
   201→This will render as:
   202→
   203→> - [x] Complete task
   204→> - [ ] Incomplete task
   205→
   206→See the specification for the [task list extension] for more details.
   207→
   208→### Smart punctuation
   209→
   210→Some ASCII punctuation sequences will be automatically turned into fancy Unicode
   211→characters:
   212→
   213→| ASCII sequence | Unicode |
   214→|----------------|---------|
   215→| `--`           | –       |
   216→| `---`          | —       |
   217→| `...`          | …       |
   218→| `"`            | “ or ”, depending on context |
   219→| `'`            | ‘ or ’, depending on context |
   220→
   221→So, no need to manually enter those Unicode characters!
   222→
   223→This feature is enabled by default.
   224→To disable it, see the [`output.html.smart-punctuation`] config option.
   225→
   226→[strikethrough]: https://github.github.com/gfm/#strikethrough-extension-
   227→[tables]: https://github.github.com/gfm/#tables-extension-
   228→[task list extension]: https://github.github.com/gfm/#task-list-items-extension-
   229→[`output.html.smart-punctuation`]: configuration/renderers.md#html-renderer-options
   230→
   231→### Heading attributes
   232→
   233→Headings can have a custom HTML ID and classes. This lets you maintain the same ID even if you change the heading's text, it also lets you add multiple classes in the heading.
   234→
   235→Example:
   236→```md
   237→# Example heading { #first .class1 .class2 }
   238→```
   239→
   240→This makes the level 1 heading with the content `Example heading`, ID `first`, and classes `class1` and `class2`. Note that the attributes should be space-separated.
   241→
   242→More information can be found in the [heading attrs spec page](https://github.com/raphlinus/pulldown-cmark/blob/master/pulldown-cmark/specs/heading_attrs.txt).
   243→
   244→### Definition lists
   245→
   246→Definition lists can be used for things like glossary entries. The term is listed on a line by itself, followed by one or more definitions. Each definition must begin with a `:` (after 0-2 spaces).
   247→
   248→Example:
   249→
   250→```md
   251→term A
   252→  : This is a definition of term A. Text
   253→    can span multiple lines.
   254→
   255→term B
   256→  : This is a definition of term B.
   257→  : This has more than one definition.
   258→```
   259→
   260→This will render as:
   261→
   262→term A
   263→  : This is a definition of term A. Text
   264→    can span multiple lines.
   265→
   266→term B
   267→  : This is a definition of term B.
   268→  : This has more than one definition.
   269→
   270→Terms are clickable just like headers, which will set the browser's URL to point directly to that term.
   271→
   272→See the [definition lists spec](https://github.com/pulldown-cmark/pulldown-cmark/blob/HEAD/pulldown-cmark/specs/definition_lists.txt) for more information on the specifics of the syntax. See the [Wikipedia guidelines for glossaries](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Glossaries#General_guidelines_for_writing_glossaries) for some guidelines on how to write a glossary.
   273→
   274→This feature is enabled by default.
   275→To disable it, see the [`output.html.definition-lists`] config option.
   276→
   277→[`output.html.definition-lists`]: configuration/renderers.md#html-renderer-options
   278→
   279→### Admonitions
   280→
   281→An admonition is a special type of callout or notice block used to highlight important information. It is written as a blockquote with a special tag on the first line.
   282→
   283→```md
   284→> [!NOTE]
   285→> General information or additional context.
   286→
   287→> [!TIP]
   288→> A helpful suggestion or best practice.
   289→
   290→> [!IMPORTANT]
   291→> Key information that shouldn't be missed.
   292→
   293→> [!WARNING]
   294→> Critical information that highlights a potential risk.
   295→
   296→> [!CAUTION]
   297→> Information about potential issues that require caution.
   298→```
   299→
   300→These will render as:
   301→
   302→> [!NOTE]
   303→> General information or additional context.
   304→
   305→> [!TIP]
   306→> A helpful suggestion or best practice.
   307→
   308→> [!IMPORTANT]
   309→> Key information that shouldn't be missed.
   310→
   311→> [!WARNING]
   312→> Critical information that highlights a potential risk.
   313→
   314→> [!CAUTION]
   315→> Information about potential issues that require caution.
   316→
   317→This feature is enabled by default.
   318→To disable it, see the [`output.html.admonitions`] config option.
   319→
   320→[`output.html.admonitions`]: configuration/renderers.md#html-renderer-options
format/mathjax.md
     1→# MathJax support
     2→
     3→mdBook has optional support for math equations through
     4→[MathJax](https://www.mathjax.org/).
     5→
     6→To enable MathJax, you need to add the `mathjax-support` key to your `book.toml`
     7→under the `output.html` section.
     8→
     9→```toml
    10→[output.html]
    11→mathjax-support = true
    12→```
    13→
    14→>**Note:** The usual delimiters MathJax uses are not yet supported. You can't
    15→currently use `$$ ... $$` as delimiters and the `\[ ... \]` delimiters need an
    16→extra backslash to work. Hopefully this limitation will be lifted soon.
    17→
    18→>**Note:** When you use double backslashes in MathJax blocks (for example in
    19→> commands such as `\begin{cases} \frac 1 2 \\ \frac 3 4 \end{cases}`) you need
    20→> to add _two extra_ backslashes (e.g., `\begin{cases} \frac 1 2 \\\\ \frac 3 4
    21→> \end{cases}`).
    22→
    23→
    24→### Inline equations
    25→Inline equations are delimited by `\\(` and `\\)`. So for example, to render the
    26→following inline equation \\( \int x dx = \frac{x^2}{2} + C \\) you would write
    27→the following:
    28→```
    29→\\( \int x dx = \frac{x^2}{2} + C \\)
    30→```
    31→
    32→### Block equations
    33→Block equations are delimited by `\\[` and `\\]`. To render the following
    34→equation
    35→
    36→\\[ \mu = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=0} x_i \\]
    37→
    38→
    39→you would write:
    40→
    41→```bash
    42→\\[ \mu = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=0} x_i \\]
    43→```
format/mdbook.md
     1→# mdBook-specific features
     2→
     3→## Hiding code lines
     4→
     5→There is a feature in mdBook that lets you hide code lines by prepending them with a specific prefix.
     6→
     7→For the Rust language, you can prefix lines with `# ` (`#` followed by a space) to hide them [like you would with Rustdoc][rustdoc-hide].
     8→This prefix can be escaped with `##` to prevent the hiding of a line that should begin with the literal string `# ` (see [Rustdoc's docs][rustdoc-hide] for more details)
     9→
    10→[rustdoc-hide]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/rustdoc/write-documentation/documentation-tests.html#hiding-portions-of-the-example
    11→
    12→```bash
    13→# fn main() {
    14→    let x = 5;
    15→    let y = 6;
    16→
    17→    println!("{}", x + y);
    18→# }
    19→```
    20→
    21→Will render as
    22→
    23→```rust
    24→# fn main() {
    25→    let x = 5;
    26→    let y = 6;
    27→
    28→    println!("{}", x + y);
    29→# }
    30→```
    31→
    32→When you tap or hover the mouse over the code block, there will be an eyeball icon (<i class="fa fa-eye"></i>) which will toggle the visibility of the hidden lines.
    33→
    34→By default, this only works for code examples that are annotated with `rust`.
    35→However, you can define custom prefixes for other languages by adding a new line-hiding prefix in your `book.toml` with the language name and prefix character(s):
    36→
    37→```toml
    38→[output.html.code.hidelines]
    39→python = "~"
    40→```
    41→
    42→The prefix will hide any lines that begin with the given prefix. With the python prefix shown above, this:
    43→
    44→```bash
    45→~hidden()
    46→nothidden():
    47→~    hidden()
    48→    ~hidden()
    49→    nothidden()
    50→```
    51→
    52→will render as
    53→
    54→```python
    55→~hidden()
    56→nothidden():
    57→~    hidden()
    58→    ~hidden()
    59→    nothidden()
    60→```
    61→
    62→This behavior can be overridden locally with a different prefix. This has the same effect as above:
    63→
    64→~~~markdown
    65→```python,hidelines=!!!
    66→!!!hidden()
    67→nothidden():
    68→!!!    hidden()
    69→    !!!hidden()
    70→    nothidden()
    71→```
    72→~~~
    73→
    74→## Rust playground
    75→
    76→Rust language code blocks will automatically get a play button (<i class="fas fa-play"></i>) which will execute the code and display the output just below the code block.
    77→This works by sending the code to the [Rust Playground].
    78→
    79→```rust
    80→println!("Hello, World!");
    81→```
    82→
    83→If there is no `main` function, then the code is automatically wrapped inside one.
    84→
    85→If you wish to disable the play button for a code block, you can include the `noplayground` option on the code block like this:
    86→
    87→~~~markdown
    88→```rust,noplayground
    89→let mut name = String::new();
    90→std::io::stdin().read_line(&mut name).expect("failed to read line");
    91→println!("Hello {}!", name);
    92→```
    93→~~~
    94→
    95→Or, if you wish to disable the play button for all code blocks in your book, you can write the config to the `book.toml` like this.
    96→
    97→```toml
    98→[output.html.playground]
    99→runnable = false
   100→```
   101→
   102→## Rust code block attributes
   103→
   104→Additional attributes can be included in Rust code blocks with comma, space, or tab-separated terms just after the language term. For example:
   105→
   106→~~~markdown
   107→```rust,ignore
   108→# This example won't be tested.
   109→panic!("oops!");
   110→```
   111→~~~
   112→
   113→These are particularly important when using [`mdbook test`] to test Rust examples.
   114→These use the same attributes as [rustdoc attributes], with a few additions:
   115→
   116→* `editable` --- Enables the [editor].
   117→* `noplayground` --- Removes the play button, but will still be tested.
   118→* `mdbook-runnable` --- Forces the play button to be displayed.
   119→  This is intended to be combined with the `ignore` attribute for examples that should not be tested, but you want to allow the reader to run.
   120→* `ignore` --- Will not be tested and no play button is shown, but it is still highlighted as Rust syntax.
   121→* `should_panic` --- When executed, it should produce a panic.
   122→* `no_run` --- The code is compiled when tested, but it is not run.
   123→  The play button is also not shown.
   124→* `compile_fail` --- The code should fail to compile.
   125→* `edition2015`, `edition2018`, `edition2021`, `edition2024` --- Forces the use of a specific Rust edition.
   126→  See [`rust.edition`] to set this globally.
   127→
   128→[`mdbook test`]: ../cli/test.md
   129→[rustdoc attributes]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/rustdoc/documentation-tests.html#attributes
   130→[editor]: theme/editor.md
   131→[`rust.edition`]: configuration/general.md#rust-options
   132→
   133→## Including files
   134→
   135→With the following syntax, you can include files into your book:
   136→
   137→```hbs
   138→\{{#include file.rs}}
   139→```
   140→
   141→The path to the file has to be relative from the current source file.
   142→
   143→mdBook will interpret included files as Markdown. Since the include command
   144→is usually used for inserting code snippets and examples, you will often
   145→wrap the command with ```` ``` ```` to display the file contents without
   146→interpreting them.
   147→
   148→````hbs
   149→```
   150→\{{#include file.rs}}
   151→```
   152→````
   153→
   154→## Including portions of a file
   155→Often you only need a specific part of the file, e.g. relevant lines for an
   156→example. We support four different modes of partial includes:
   157→
   158→```hbs
   159→\{{#include file.rs:2}}
   160→\{{#include file.rs::10}}
   161→\{{#include file.rs:2:}}
   162→\{{#include file.rs:2:10}}
   163→```
   164→
   165→The first command only includes the second line from file `file.rs`. The second
   166→command includes all lines up to line 10, i.e. the lines from 11 till the end of
   167→the file are omitted. The third command includes all lines from line 2, i.e. the
   168→first line is omitted. The last command includes the excerpt of `file.rs`
   169→consisting of lines 2 to 10.
   170→
   171→To avoid breaking your book when modifying included files, you can also
   172→include a specific section using anchors instead of line numbers.
   173→An anchor is a pair of matching lines. The line beginning an anchor must
   174→match the regex `ANCHOR:\s*[\w_-]+` and similarly the ending line must match
   175→the regex `ANCHOR_END:\s*[\w_-]+`. This allows you to put anchors in
   176→any kind of commented line.
   177→
   178→Consider the following file to include:
   179→```rs
   180→/* ANCHOR: all */
   181→
   182→// ANCHOR: component
   183→struct Paddle {
   184→    hello: f32,
   185→}
   186→// ANCHOR_END: component
   187→
   188→////////// ANCHOR: system
   189→impl System for MySystem { ... }
   190→////////// ANCHOR_END: system
   191→
   192→/* ANCHOR_END: all */
   193→```
   194→
   195→Then in the book, all you have to do is:
   196→````hbs
   197→Here is a component:
   198→```rust,no_run,noplayground
   199→\{{#include file.rs:component}}
   200→```
   201→
   202→Here is a system:
   203→```rust,no_run,noplayground
   204→\{{#include file.rs:system}}
   205→```
   206→
   207→This is the full file.
   208→```rust,no_run,noplayground
   209→\{{#include file.rs:all}}
   210→```
   211→````
   212→
   213→Lines containing anchor patterns inside the included anchor are ignored.
   214→
   215→## Including a file but initially hiding all except specified lines
   216→
   217→The `rustdoc_include` helper is for including code from external Rust files that contain complete
   218→examples, but only initially showing particular lines specified with line numbers or anchors in the
   219→same way as with `include`.
   220→
   221→The lines not in the line number range or between the anchors will still be included, but they will
   222→be prefaced with `#`. This way, a reader can expand the snippet to see the complete example, and
   223→Rustdoc will use the complete example when you run `mdbook test`.
   224→
   225→For example, consider a file named `file.rs` that contains this Rust program:
   226→
   227→```rust
   228→fn main() {
   229→    let x = add_one(2);
   230→    assert_eq!(x, 3);
   231→}
   232→
   233→fn add_one(num: i32) -> i32 {
   234→    num + 1
   235→}
   236→```
   237→
   238→We can include a snippet that initially shows only line 2 by using this syntax:
   239→
   240→````hbs
   241→To call the `add_one` function, we pass it an `i32` and bind the returned value to `x`:
   242→
   243→```rust
   244→\{{#rustdoc_include file.rs:2}}
   245→```
   246→````
   247→
   248→This would have the same effect as if we had manually inserted the code and hidden all but line 2
   249→using `#`:
   250→
   251→````hbs
   252→To call the `add_one` function, we pass it an `i32` and bind the returned value to `x`:
   253→
   254→```rust
   255→# fn main() {
   256→    let x = add_one(2);
   257→#     assert_eq!(x, 3);
   258→# }
   259→#
   260→# fn add_one(num: i32) -> i32 {
   261→#     num + 1
   262→# }
   263→```
   264→````
   265→
   266→That is, it looks like this (click the "expand" icon to see the rest of the file):
   267→
   268→```rust
   269→# fn main() {
   270→    let x = add_one(2);
   271→#     assert_eq!(x, 3);
   272→# }
   273→#
   274→# fn add_one(num: i32) -> i32 {
   275→#     num + 1
   276→# }
   277→```
   278→
   279→## Inserting runnable Rust files
   280→
   281→With the following syntax, you can insert runnable Rust files into your book:
   282→
   283→```hbs
   284→\{{#playground file.rs}}
   285→```
   286→
   287→The path to the Rust file has to be relative from the current source file.
   288→
   289→When play is clicked, the code snippet will be sent to the [Rust Playground] to be
   290→compiled and run. The result is sent back and displayed directly underneath the
   291→code.
   292→
   293→Here is what a rendered code snippet looks like:
   294→
   295→{{#playground example.rs}}
   296→
   297→Any additional values passed after the filename will be included as attributes of the code block.
   298→For example `\{{#playground example.rs editable}}` will create the code block like the following:
   299→
   300→~~~markdown
   301→```rust,editable
   302→# Contents of example.rs here.
   303→```
   304→~~~
   305→
   306→And the `editable` attribute will enable the [editor] as described at [Rust code block attributes](#rust-code-block-attributes).
   307→
   308→[Rust Playground]: https://play.rust-lang.org/
   309→
   310→## Controlling page \<title\>
   311→
   312→A chapter can set a \<title\> that is different from its entry in the table of
   313→contents (sidebar) by including a `\{{#title ...}}` near the top of the page.
   314→
   315→```hbs
   316→\{{#title My Title}}
   317→```
   318→
   319→## HTML classes provided by mdBook
   320→
   321→<img class="right" src="images/rust-logo-blk.svg" alt="The Rust logo">
   322→
   323→### `class="left"` and `"right"`
   324→
   325→These classes are provided by default, for inline HTML to float images.
   326→
   327→```html
   328→<img class="right" src="images/rust-logo-blk.svg" alt="The Rust logo">
   329→```
   330→
   331→### `class="hidden"`
   332→
   333→HTML tags with class `hidden` will not be shown.
   334→
   335→```html
   336→<div class="hidden">This will not be seen.</div>
   337→```
   338→
   339→<div class="hidden">This will not be seen.</div>
   340→
   341→## Font-Awesome icons
   342→
   343→mdBook includes a copy of version 6 of [Font Awesome Free's](https://fontawesome.com)
   344→MIT-licensed SVG files. It emulates the `<i>` syntax, but converts the results
   345→to inline SVG. Only the regular, solid, and brands icons are included; paid
   346→features like the light icons are not.
   347→
   348→For example, given this HTML syntax:
   349→
   350→```hbs
   351→The result looks like this: <i class="fa-solid fa-print"></i>
   352→```
   353→
   354→The result looks like this: <i class="fa-solid fa-print"></i>
   355→
   356→See the [free icon set](https://fontawesome.com/v6/search) for the available icons.
format/summary.md
     1→# SUMMARY.md
     2→
     3→The summary file is used by mdBook to know what chapters to include, in what
     4→order they should appear, what their hierarchy is and where the source files
     5→are. Without this file, there is no book.
     6→
     7→This markdown file must be named `SUMMARY.md`. Its formatting
     8→is very strict and must follow the structure outlined below to allow for easy
     9→parsing. Any element not specified below, be it formatting or textual, is likely
    10→to be ignored at best, or may cause an error when attempting to build the book.
    11→
    12→### Structure
    13→
    14→1. ***Title*** - While optional, it's common practice to begin with a title, generally <code
    15→   class="language-markdown"># Summary</code>. This is ignored by the parser however, and
    16→   can be omitted.
    17→   ```markdown
    18→   # Summary
    19→   ```
    20→
    21→1. ***Prefix Chapter*** - Before the main numbered chapters, prefix chapters can be added
    22→   that will not be numbered. This is useful for forewords,
    23→   introductions, etc. There are, however, some constraints. Prefix chapters cannot be
    24→   nested; they should all be on the root level. And you cannot add
    25→   prefix chapters once you have added numbered chapters.
    26→   ```markdown
    27→   [A Prefix Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown.md)
    28→
    29→   - [First Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown2.md)
    30→   ```
    31→
    32→1. ***Part Title*** -
    33→   Level 1 headers can be used as a title for the following numbered chapters.
    34→   This can be used to logically separate different sections of the book.
    35→   The title is rendered as unclickable text.
    36→   Titles are optional, and the numbered chapters can be broken into as many parts as desired.
    37→   Part titles must be h1 headers (one `#`), other heading levels are ignored.
    38→   ```markdown
    39→   # My Part Title
    40→
    41→   - [First Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown.md)
    42→   ```
    43→
    44→1. ***Numbered Chapter*** - Numbered chapters outline the main content of the book
    45→   and can be nested, resulting in a nice hierarchy
    46→   (chapters, sub-chapters, etc.).
    47→   ```markdown
    48→   # Title of Part
    49→
    50→   - [First Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown.md)
    51→   - [Second Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown2.md)
    52→      - [Sub Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown3.md)
    53→
    54→   # Title of Another Part
    55→
    56→   - [Another Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown4.md)
    57→   ```
    58→   Numbered chapters can be denoted with either `-` or `*` (do not mix delimiters). 
    59→   
    60→1. ***Suffix Chapter*** - Like prefix chapters, suffix chapters are unnumbered, but they come after 
    61→   numbered chapters.
    62→   ```markdown
    63→   - [Last Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown.md)
    64→
    65→   [Title of Suffix Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown2.md)
    66→   ```
    67→
    68→1. ***Draft chapters*** - Draft chapters are chapters without a file and thus content.
    69→   The purpose of a draft chapter is to signal future chapters still to be written.
    70→   Or when still laying out the structure of the book to avoid creating the files
    71→   while you are still changing the structure of the book a lot.
    72→   Draft chapters will be rendered in the HTML renderer as disabled links in the table
    73→   of contents, as you can see for the next chapter in the table of contents on the left.
    74→   Draft chapters are written like normal chapters but without writing the path to the file.
    75→   ```markdown
    76→   - [Draft Chapter]()
    77→   ```
    78→
    79→1. ***Separators*** - Separators can be added before, in between, and after any other element. They result
    80→   in an HTML rendered line in the built table of contents.  A separator is
    81→   a line containing exclusively dashes and at least three of them: `---`.
    82→   ```markdown
    83→   # My Part Title
    84→   
    85→   [A Prefix Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown.md)
    86→
    87→   ---
    88→
    89→   - [First Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown2.md)
    90→   ```
    91→  
    92→
    93→### Example
    94→
    95→Below is the markdown source for the `SUMMARY.md` for this guide, with the resulting table
    96→of contents as rendered to the left.
    97→
    98→```markdown
    99→{{#include ../SUMMARY.md}}
   100→```
format/theme/README.md
     1→# Theme
     2→
     3→The default renderer uses a [handlebars](https://handlebarsjs.com) template to
     4→render your markdown files and comes with a default theme included in the mdBook
     5→binary.
